"NOT FOUND"|"The Cavalry: Caesar here mentions for the first time the cavalry. It is said he had no horsemen when he came into*Gaul, but he commenced at once and raised a force of about 4000, as stated, from the Province and especially from the Aidui and their client tribes. Others say that there was always a regular contingent of cavalry in every legion, mercenary troops from Spain and Germany, as well as from Gaul. These contingent forces of cavalry, however, are rarely mentioned, Caesar***s pride being in his own Roman legionaries. Whatever the fact may be concerning the existence at Caesar***s time of a regular cavalry, it is certain that temporary levies were made from Gallic states subject or favorable to Rome. These probably disbanded on the approach of winter, appearing again in the spring."

