"NOT FOUND"|"The Belgae: The Belgian tribes commonly claimed German origin. Strabo calls them 7epfiaviKdv **0vos, a *** Germanic people.*** And Hirtius, in the Eighth Book, says, *** They are not much different from the Germans.***The Celtae: These are the people whom the Romans meant especially when they spoke of Gauls. In Caesar***s time they had fallen from the position of headship of all France to a third part in the territorial division which he describes. They called themselves *** Children of Night,*** whence the origin of our expression fortnight and se'nnight *** in accordance with the Gallic manner of reckoning time by night. Modem scholars have learned a little of their language from proper names and inscriptions, which show them to be a branch of the Aryan race, which swept westward from Asia over Europe long before the time of Greece or Rome. For the EnglishNOTESmeaning of some Celtic proper names, see the Vocabulary of this book."

