"NOT FOUND"|"Thus, the outlines of the camp having been already marked out with great accuracy, no time was lost after the arrival of the army; laying aside all instruments of war, the soldiers began to dig a ditch or moat (fossa), about nine feet wide and six feet deep. With this earth they built also a wall {vallum), usually about six feet above the level of the ground, and six or eight feet broad on the top, to enable standing-room for the soldiers in event of an assault on the camp. To strengthen the defenses, branches of trees, stakes, and even logs were imbedded and the sides covered with sods, and along the outer edge of the top was a line of green stakes driven into the ground, and the branches intertwined, rising four or five feet above the top, and forming a breastwork. For a cross-section view of this complete structure, see cut on page 44."

