"NOT FOUND"|"Max. pot. itineribus: He travelled sometimes a hundred miles a day, either walking at the head of his legions, or mounted on his own favorite horse, which would suffer no one but his master to mount him, or borne in his litter while dictating to four or sometimes seven amanuenses *** reading, writing, dictating, and listening all at once. ***Under the rains of Gaul, swimming its rivers, climbing its mountains on foot, and making his bed among rains and snows in its forests and morasses,*** of which Michelet, Suetonius, and Plutarch all tell us, he spared himself none of the hardships of the common soldier."

